**THE HISTORY OF MONEY** 

**Activity type** 		GAME

 

**Time**			40 minutes

 

**Source		**My First Bitcoin - Chapter 3.0

**Grouping**



* 5-8 participants
* Whole group

**Materials & Equipment**



* Money throughout the Ages - visual aid
* Commodity money - Coffee beans
* Trade Objects
* Shopping List
* [Countdown clock/cellphone](https://vclock.com/timer/)

**Key Concepts**



* Functions of Money (esp. Medium of Exchange, Unit of Account)
* Properties of Money (esp. Acceptability, Fungibility, & Scarcity)

**Blind Spots**



* Make sure it will be possible to correctly trade
* Make sure objects on list match objects on table

**Connections with Other Workshops**





**PROCEDURE**

* Participant requirements	N/A
* Personal introduction	About yourself



* Anticipatory Set		
  What is money?
  Why do we need money?
  What gives money its “value”?
  Who controls the money?

* Objective and purpose in student’s words
    * This workshop will help you understand the function of money and the effects of inflation.
1. INTRODUCE the workshop - Use the **Visual Aid** to show participants the evolution of money.
2. ILLUSTRATE -  If there are examples within your community, use them to make the workshop more understandable and thus relate more to your students' reality. (ie. Talk about Canada and the genesis of the Canadian dollar)

<span style="text-decoration:underline;">ACTIVITY</span>									<span style="text-decoration:underline;">30 minutes</span>



1. **ROUND 1 - TRADE**
    1. DISTRIBUTE MATERIALS -  Each participant receives a **Shopping list **(what they need) and a random allocation of **Trade objects **(what they have).
    2. BARTER - Participants offer each other items that they don’t need in exchange for items that they do need.
    3. COUNTDOWN - set a timer for <span style="text-decoration:underline;">10 minutes</span> (one block) and see if the group can trade what they have for what they need. 
    4. REFLECT - Ask participants if they found the activity easy or difficult. 
    5. COLLECT - Collect in all **Shopping lists** and **Trade objects**.

2. **ROUND 2 - COMMODITY MONEY**
    6. DISTRIBUTE MATERIALS -  Again, each participant receives a **Shopping list** and a random allocation of **Trade objects**. 
    7. INTRODUCE COMMODITY MONEY - Use **Coffee beans** to help facilitate trade. Explain that the coffee beans will act as the local money. 
    8. COUNTDOWN - set a timer for <span style="text-decoration:underline;">10 minutes</span> and see if the group can trade what they have for what they need. 
    9. REFLECT - Ask participants if they found the activity easier. Why?
    10. COLLECT - Collect in all shopping lists and objects.

3. **ROUND 3 - INFLATE**
    11. DISTRIBUTE MATERIALS -  Again, each participant receives a shopping list and a random allocation of trade objects. 
    12. INFLATE - Add extra coffee beans to each participant’s budget.  
    13. COUNTDOWN - set a timer for <span style="text-decoration:underline;">10 minutes</span> and see if the group can trade what they have for what they need. 
    14. REFLECT - Ask participants if they found the activity easy or difficult. 
    15. COLLECT - Collect in all shopping lists and objects.


1. Using the **Visual aide** to show the evolution of money in Canada. Explain the money supply.
2. Explain the fixed supply (21M) & divisibility (sats) of Bitcoin and show the graph of the CAD M2 money supply.

<span style="text-decoration:underline;">CLOSE</span> 									<span style="text-decoration:underline;">4-5 minutes </span>



    * Any questions?
    * Mention connected workshops - WORKSHOP 6 - Send and Receive
    * Ask where people are from
    * Connect them with other locals-meetups-businesses etc
    * Reset station for the next workshop.

**<span style="text-decoration:underline;">NOTES</span>**
